06019nam a22007095i 9781805390091DE-B159720240306014423.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97818053900917 a10.1515/97818053900912doi  a(DE-B1597)651446  a(OCoLC)1408964453  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aHN49.R33bR477 2024 7aSOC0510002bisacsh04a303.484094223/eng/2023110900aResisting Radicalisation? :bUnderstanding Young People's Journeys through Radicalising Milieus /ced. by Hilary Pilkington. 1aNew York ;aOxford : bBerghahn Books, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (324 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgements -- tIntroduction. Beyond Endpoints: Rethinking How and Why to Study Radicalisation -- tPart I. Cross-European Perspectives on Trajectories of (Non)Radicalisation -- tChapter 1. Non-Radicalisation under a Magnifying Glass: A Cross-European 'Milieu Perspective' on Resistance to Islamist Radical Messaging -- tChapter 2. Situating Trajectories of 'Extreme-Right' (Non)Radicalisation: The Role of the Radical Milieu -- tPart II. Sites and Sources of (Non)Radicalisation -- tChapter 3. What Is the Connection between Inequalities and Radicalisation? Reviewing the Evidence Base -- tChapter 4. Islam and Violence in Greek Society: The Stigmatisation of Muslims, the Extreme Right and Resistance to Reciprocal Radicalisation -- tChapter 5. Family, Relatives and Friendship as Channels of (Non)Radicalisation in the Narratives of the Second Urban Generation of North Caucasian Youth -- tPart III. Situational and Interactional Dynamics of (Non)Radicalisation -- tChapter 6. Situational and Interactional Dynamics in Trajectories of (Non)Radicalisation: A Micro-Level Analysis of Violence in an 'Extreme-Right' Milieu -- tChapter 7. Trajectories of (Non)Radicalisation in a French Prison -- tChapter 8. Responses to Radical(ising) Messages and Their Messengers by Young Marksmen and Their Clubs: From Rejection to Normalisation -- tConclusion. Has Radicalisation Research Reached Its Endpoint? -- tAppendix. Overview of Milieus Studied -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aThis landmark volume of extensive empirical research conducted across Europe explains how, and why, young people become engaged in radical(ising) milieus but also resist radicalisation into violent extremism. Offering a critical perspective on the concept of radicalisation, this volume views it from the perspective of social actors who engage in radicalising milieus but for the most part have not crossed the threshold into violent extremism. It brings together contributions conducted as part of a cross-European (including France, Germany, the Netherlands, Greece, Russia, Turkey, the UK, and beyond) study of young people's engagement in 'extreme right' and 'Islamist' milieus. It argues that radicalisation is best understood as a relational concept reflecting a social process rooted in relational inequalities but also shaped by interactional and situational dynamics, which not only facilitate but also constrain radicalisation.  afunded by University of Manchester  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aRadicalismxReligious aspectsxIslam. 0aRadicalizationxSocial aspectszEurope. 0aRadicalizationzEuropexPrevention. 0aRadicalizationzEurope. 0aYouthxPolitical activityzEurope. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Violence in Society.2bisacsh1 aConti, Bartolomeo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDechesne, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.go